kinetic energy T =3D=20
p<SUP>2</SUP>/2m, and the potential energy V =3D =
m=CF=89<SUP>2</SUP>x<SUP>2</SUP>/2.=20
The Hamiltonian H(p,q) =3D T + V.</P>
<P>In quantum mechanics, the state of the oscillator is described by an=20
amplitude =CE=A8 that obeys the equation of motion =
(ih/2=CF=80)d=CE=A8/dt =3D H=CE=A8, where H is an=20
operator formed from the operators p and x. In the Schr=C3=B6dinger =
picture, the=20
state is described by the generalized coordinate x, and the momentum is =
the=20
operator p =3D -(ih/2=CF=80)d/dx. A state of definite energy E satisfies =
the relation=20
H=CE=A8 =3D E=CE=A8, and is called an <I>energy eigenstate</I>. Since H =
does not contain the=20
time, =CE=A8 can be expressed as the product of a time factor and a =
space factor =CF=88.=20
The equation of motion shows that the time factor is exp(i2=CF=80Et/h) =
for a state of=20
this kind, which represents a steady change of phase at frequency E/h. =
It is the=20
complex nature of =CE=A8 that allows it to express the complete behavior =
of the=20
oscillator with the x coordinate alone, instead of the position and =
momentum=20
separately. The operators for p and x satisfy xp - px =3D ih/2=CF=80; =
that is, they do=20
not commute, which is a fundamental property.</P>
<P>Since the time function factors out, =CF=88 satisfies H=CF=88 =3D =
E=CF=88, or=20
-(h<SUP>2</SUP>/8=CF=80<SUP>2</SUP>m)d<SUP>2</SUP>=CF=88dx<SUP>2</SUP> + =

m=CF=89<SUP>2</SUP>x<SUP>2</SUP>=CF=88/2 =3D E=CF=88. This is the =
Schr=C3=B6dinger Equation, and =CF=88(x)=20
is the Schr=C3=B6dinger wave function. If we put u =3D x=E2=88=9A=CE=B1, =
where =CE=B1 =3D 2=CF=80m=CF=89/h, this=20
equation becomes</P>
<P align=3Dcenter>d<SUP>2</SUP>=CF=88/du<SUP>2</SUP> + (2E/h=CE=BD - =
u<SUP>2</SUP>)=CF=88 =3D 0</P>
<P>From what we said above, we see that 2E/h=CE=BD =3D 2n + 1, and =
