C<SUB>n</SUB>exp(-u<SUP>2</SUP>/2)H<SUB>n</SUB>(u), where C<SUB>n</SUB> =
is=20
chosen so that the integral of the square of =CF=88 from -=E2=88=9E to =
+=E2=88=9E is unity; this is=20
said to <I>normalize</I> the wave function. For energy eigenstates such =
as this,=20
we can always choose =CF=88 real. The energy of the oscillator takes the =
values E =3D=20
h=CE=BD(n + 1/2). In the ground state, n=3D 0, there remains the =
<I>zero-point</I>=20
energy h=CE=BD/2. This unexpected and quite real result was one of the =
triumphs of=20
quantum mechanics.</P>
<P>The energy eigenstates of the harmonic oscillator are by no means the =
only or=20
the usually observed states. They are mainly useful in expanding more =
general=20
states in terms of the energy eigenstates, and other theoretical =
developments.=20
In particular, it is impossible to realize a macroscopic energy =
eigenstate, so=20
we never see the nodes or the spreading in daily life. The widest =
applications=20
of this theory are to optics and radiation, incidentally.</P>
